       Before exiting the window environment, follow the recom-
       mended procedure to exit any application programs and stop
       any commands that may be running in terminal windows.  When
       you have a command prompt in each terminal window, follow
       your system administrator's instructions for quitting Motif.

       SSSStttteeeepppp 1111:::: PPPPrrrreeeeppppaaaarrrriiiinnnngggg ttttoooo EEEExxxxiiiitttt

       First, exit any application programs running in terminal
       windows. This avoids the possible loss of data due to
       improperly stopping a program.

       When you exit a program, the command-line prompt returns to
       the terminal window.  (However, if you started the program
       automatically or from a menu, exiting will also remove the
       terminal window.  This is proper behavior.)  Choosing Close
       from the window menu immediately stops any program running
       in the window.  Interrupting a program like this may cause
       it to lose data.  For example, if you were running a word
       processor in the window, you could lose any unsaved changes.
       However, you can close the clock, the load histogram, or an
       ``idle'' terminal window (one showing a command prompt) with
       no ill effect.

       SSSStttteeeepppp 2222:::: SSSSttttooooppppppppiiiinnnngggg XXXX aaaannnndddd tttthhhheeee MMMMWWWWMMMM

       After exiting all programs, follow the procedure given to
       you by your system administrator to stop your system.

       This removes from the screen all terminal windows (as well
       as the windows for clocks, load histograms, and similar win-
       dowed programs).  A moment later the root window disappears.

       If a command-line prompt appears, you have exited the X Win-
       dow System, but you are still logged into your computer.  If
       you see llllooooggggiiiinnnn::::, then you have completely logged out of your
       computer.














